# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: avar-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:avar-language/abaza-language] Abaza is spoken by approximately 35,000 people in Russia, where it is written in a Cyrillic alphabet, as well as another 10,000 in Turkey, where the Latin script is used.
[src:avar-language/abaza-language] It consists of two dialects, the Ashkherewa dialect and the T'ap'anta dialect, which is the literary standard.
[src:avar-language/abaza-language] The language also consists of five subdialects known as Psyzh-Krasnovostok, Abazakt, Apsua, Kubin-Elburgan and Kuvin.
[src:avar-language/abaza-language] Abaza, like its relatives in the family of Northwest Caucasian languages, is a highly agglutinative language.
[src:avar-language/abaza-language] For example, the verb in the English sentence "He couldn't make them give it back to her" contains four arguments (a term used in valency grammar): *he*, *them*, *it*, *to her*.
[src:avar-language/abaza-language] Abaza marks arguments morphologically, and incorporates all four arguments as pronominal prefixes on the verb.
[src:avar-language/abaza-language] It has a large consonantal inventory (63 phonemes) coupled with a minimal vowel inventory (two vowels).
[src:avar-language/abaza-language] It is very closely related to Abkhaz, but it preserves a few phonemes which Abkhaz lacks, such as a voiced pharyngeal fricative.
[src:avar-language/abaza-language] Work on Abaza has been carried out by W.
[src:avar-language/abaza-language] Allen, Brian O'Herin, and John Colarusso.
[src:avar-language/abaza-language] Different forms of cultural assimilation contributed to its fall in use in areas of Russia, and over time its overall endangerment.
[src:avar-language/abaza-language] The language can be broken into five different dialects and has several unique grammatical approaches to languages.
[src:avar-language/abaza-language] The Abaza language was at its peak usage in the mid to late 19th century.
[src:avar-language/abaza-language] Abaza speakers along the Greater and Lesser Laba, Urup, and Greater and Lesser Zelenchuk rivers are from a wave of migrants in the 17th to 18th centuries who represent the Abaza speakers of today.
[src:avar-language/abaza-language] The end of the Great Caucasian War in 1864 provided Russia with power and control of the local regions and contributed to the decrease in the popularity of pre-existing local languages prior to the war.
[src:avar-language/abaza-language] The Abaza language was not a written language until the Latin alphabet was adopted in 1932–1933 to write it.
[src:avar-language/abaza-language] The Cyrillic script was later utilized to write the language in 1938.
[src:avar-language/abaza-language] A small amount of books, pamphlets, and a newspaper were published in the Abaza language afterwards.
[src:avar-language/abaza-language] The Abaza language is spoken in Russia and Turkey.
[src:avar-language/abaza-language] Although it is endangered, it is still spoken in several regions in Russia.
[src:avar-language/abaza-language] These include Kara-Pago, Kubina, Psyzh, El'burgan, Inzhich-Chukun, Koi-dan, Abaza-Khabl', Malo-Abazinka, Tapanta, Krasnovostochni, Novokuvinski, Starokuvinski, Abazakt and Ap-sua.
[src:avar-language/abaza-language] The vowels [o, a, u] may have a /j/ in front of it.
[src:avar-language/abaza-language] The vowels [e] and [i] are allophones of /a/ and /ə/ (respectively) before palatalized consonants, while the vowels [o] and [u] are allophones of /a/ and /ə/ (respectively) before labialized consonants.
[src:avar-language/abaza-language] The vowels [e], [o], [i], and [u] can also occur as variants of the sequences /aj/, /aw/, /əj/ and /əw/.
[src:avar-language/abaza-language] Abaza does not have the long low vowel found in Kabardian, preserving it as /aʕ/ or /ʕa/.
[src:avar-language/abaza-language] Around the late 19th to early 20th centuries, there were attempts to write Abaza with the Arabic script, but none of these attempts took hold.
[src:avar-language/abaza-language] In 1932, the first widely used Abaza alphabet was created using the Latin script.
[src:avar-language/abaza-language] Since 1938, Abaza has been written with the version of the Cyrillic alphabet shown below.
[src:avar-language/abaza-language] The digraphs Лӏ and Фӏ are dialectal, and are therefore absent from the literary language and the official alphabet.
[src:avar-language/abaza-language] Sultan Laguchev, a singer-songwriter famous in Russia, writes and performs songs in the Abaza language, including "Абыгъь гӏважьква" and "БаъапI бара." He has written an additional song in Russian entitled "Мы абазины" ('We are Abazins') about Abazinia.
[src:avar-language/abjad] 'alphabet') is a writing system in which only consonants are represented by letter signs, leaving the vowels to be inferred by the reader (unless represented otherwise, such as by diacritics).
[src:avar-language/abjad] This contrasts with alphabets that provide graphemes for both consonants and vowels.
[src:avar-language/abjad] The term was introduced in 1990 by Peter T.
[src:avar-language/abjad] Other terms for the same concept include **partial phonemic script**, **segmentally linear defective phonographic script**, **consonantary**, **consonant writing**, and **consonantal alphabet**.
[src:avar-language/abjad] According to the formulations of Peter T.
[src:avar-language/abjad] Daniels, abjads differ from alphabets in that only consonants, not vowels, are represented among the basic graphemes.
[src:avar-language/abjad] Abjads differ from abugidas, another category defined by Daniels, in that in abjads, the vowel sound is *implied* by phonology, and where vowel marks exist for the system, such as niqqud for Hebrew and ḥarakāt for Arabic, their use is optional and not the dominant (or literate) form.
[src:avar-language/abjad] Abugidas mark all vowels (other than the "inherent" vowel) with a diacritic, a minor attachment to the letter, a standalone grapheme, or (in Canadian Aboriginal syllabics) by rotation of the letter.
[src:avar-language/abjad] Some abugidas use a special symbol to *suppress* the inherent vowel so that the consonant alone can be properly represented.
[src:avar-language/abjad] In a syllabary, a grapheme denotes a complete syllable, that is, either a lone vowel sound or a combination of a vowel sound with one or more consonant sounds.
[src:avar-language/abjad] The contrast of abjad versus alphabet has been rejected by other scholars because *abjad* is also used as a term for the Arabic numeral system.
[src:avar-language/abjad] Also, it may be taken as suggesting that consonantal alphabets, in contrast to e.g. the Greek alphabet, were not yet true alphabets.
[src:avar-language/abjad] Florian Coulmas, a critic of Daniels and of the abjad terminology, argues that this terminology can confuse alphabets with "transcription systems", and that there is no reason to relegate the Hebrew, Aramaic or Phoenician alphabets to second-class status as an "incomplete alphabet".
[src:avar-language/abjad] However, Daniels's terminology has found acceptance in the linguistic community.
[src:avar-language/abjad] The Proto-Sinaitic script represents the earliest-known example of alphabetic writing.
[src:avar-language/abjad] The Proto-Sinaitic script is thought to represent, or at least indicate the existence of, an early ancestor of the many later Semitic consonantal scripts which continued to develop over time into more abstract, less visually representational forms, including the Phoenician abjad.
[src:avar-language/abjad] The Phoenician abjad was a radical simplification of phonetic writing.
[src:avar-language/abjad] Unlike other scripts, such as Mesopotamian cuneiform (logographic and syllabic) and Egyptian hieroglyphs (logographic and consonantal), the Phoenician abjad consisted of only a few dozen symbols.
[src:avar-language/abjad] During these exchanges, the Phoenician script gave rise to a number of new writing systems, including the widely used Aramaic abjad and the Greek alphabet.
[src:avar-language/abjad] The Greek alphabet was later developed into several alphabets, including Etruscan, Coptic, Cyrillic, and Latin (via Etruscan), while Aramaic became the ancestor of many abjads and abugidas of Asia, particularly in and around India, Southeast Asia, and Oceania.
[src:avar-language/abjad] Impure abjads have characters for some vowels, optional vowel diacritics, or both.
[src:avar-language/abjad] The term pure abjad refers to scripts entirely lacking in vowel indicators.
[src:avar-language/abjad] This practice was at first rare and limited in scope but became increasingly common and more developed in later times.
[src:avar-language/abjad] In the 9th century BC the Greeks adapted the Phoenician script for use in their own language.
[src:avar-language/abjad] The phonetic structure of the Greek language created too many ambiguities when vowels went unrepresented, so the script was modified.
[src:avar-language/abjad] They did not need letters for the guttural sounds represented by *aleph*, *he*, *heth* or *ayin*, so these symbols were assigned vocalic values.
[src:avar-language/abjad] The letters *waw* and *yod* were also adapted into vowel signs; along with *he*, these were already used as *matres lectionis* in Phoenician.
[src:avar-language/abjad] Abugidas developed along a slightly different route.
[src:avar-language/abjad] The basic consonantal symbol was considered to have an inherent "a" vowel sound.
[src:avar-language/abjad] Hooks or short lines attached to various parts of the basic letter modify the vowel.
[src:avar-language/abjad] In this way, the South Arabian abjad evolved into the Geʽez script of Ethiopia between the 5th century BC and the 5th century AD.
[src:avar-language/abjad] Similarly, the Brāhmī abugida of the Indian subcontinent developed around the 3rd century BC (from the Aramaic abjad, it has been hypothesized).
[src:avar-language/abjad] The abjad form of writing is well-adapted to the morphological structure of the Semitic languages it was developed to write.
[src:avar-language/abjad] This is because words in Semitic languages are formed from a root consisting of (usually) three consonants, the vowels being used to indicate inflectional or derived forms.
[src:avar-language/abjad] In most cases, the absence of full glyphs for vowels makes the common root clearer, allowing readers to guess the meaning of unfamiliar words from familiar roots (especially in conjunction with context clues) and improving word recognition while reading for practiced readers.
[src:avar-language/abjad] The Hebrew abjad has also been adapted to write Jewish languages like Ladino and Yiddish.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Abkhaz is a Northwest Caucasian language and is thus related to Adyghe.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The language of Abkhaz is especially close to Abaza, and they are sometimes considered dialects of the same language, Abazgi, of which the literary dialects of Abkhaz and Abaza are simply two ends of a dialect continuum.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Grammatically, the two are very similar; however, the differences in phonology are substantial, it also contains elements characteristic of Kabardian; these are the main reasons for many others to prefer keeping the two separate, while others still refer to it as the Tapanta dialect of Abkhaz.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Chirikba mentions that there are possible indications that proto-Northwest Caucasian, could have divided firstly into proto-Circassian and to proto-Ubykh-Abkhaz; Ubykh then being the closest relative to Abkhaz, with it only later on being influenced by Circassian.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] There is not an agreed number of speakers of Abkhaz, and there are widely different numbers.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] It is agreed that today most of the Abkhaz people do not live in Abkhazia.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] In the census conducted by the Republic of Abkhazia in 2011, Abkhazians comprised 50.8% of the population, around 122,175 people; of these 92,838 spoke it natively.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Only two of the original dialects are still spoken in Abkhazia.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The Bzyp dialect is still spoken in its homeland northwest of Sukhumi, stretching from the Bzyp River to the western environs of Sukhumi and the Psyrtskha valley, whereas the Abzhywa dialect is spoken south-east of Sukhumi.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The rest of the Abkhaz speaking population inhabits other neighbouring areas.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The exact number of Abkhazians and Abkhaz speakers in Turkey is not clear.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The Turkish census denotes 13,951, but the figures are dubious, since the numbers of Abkhazians that came from the beginning of the 19th century to the middle of the 20th have been documented at around 30 thousand.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] *Ethnologue* gives 150,000 Abkhazians living in Turkey, of these 50,000 still speak the language.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The head of the Abkhaz federation says there are in between 500 and 700 thousand Abkhazians in Turkey.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Historically the dialects of Sadz, Ahchypsy and Tsabal were located in Abkhazia; Sadz being spoken from the Bzyp river to the Matsesta River, and further to the north-west bordering the Sochypsta River.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Today they are exclusively spoken in the northwestern part of Turkey, specially in the Sakarya province, it being spoken in 14 villages.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The other major place where Abkhaz is spoken is in Karachay-Cherkessia, where the Northern dialects are spoken, although there they are considered as a separate language and form the literary Abaza language.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] They are spoken by 37,831 people in Russia, mostly in the south of Stavropol Krai in the area around Kislovodsk, and in the upper Kuma river area.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Abkhaz is also spoken as a minority language around the world.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] There is a considerable number of Abkhaz speakers in Adjara in southern Georgia, with the diaspora concentrating itself around the capital Batumi, with about 982 people considering Abkhaz their first language.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] In the Russian census of 2010, 6,786 speakers of Abkhaz were reported in Russia.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] In Ukraine there are around 1,458 according to the 2001 census, but of these only 317 speak Abkhazian.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] There were also communities in Syria, Jordan and Iraq with around 5,000 Abkhazians, although this number could reach 10,000 according to the Abkhazia's Foreign Ministry.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The biggest western diaspora is in Germany, with around 5,000 speakers, but other communities are found in countries such as the United States, United Kingdom, Austria, France, Belgium and so on.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The earliest indisputable extant written records of the Abkhaz language are in the Arabic script, recorded by the Turkish traveller Evliya Çelebi in the 17th century.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Abkhaz has been used as a literary language for only about 100 years.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] It was suggested that certain inscriptions on Ancient Greek pottery which had been considered nonsense are in fact written in Abkhaz-Adydge languages.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The methodology of the research was criticised and the results called improbable.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] In 1918, Tbilisi State University became the first institution of higher education to teach Abkhazian language.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The founders of the university began to take care of the development and scientific study of the Abkhazian language.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] At the meeting of the Council of Professors held at Tbilisi State University in 1918, Ivane Javakhishvili noted the scientific importance of studying Caucasian languages.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] In 1918, by the decision of the Council of Professors, Petre Charaia was invited to teach the Abkhazian language, and from 1925, this mission was continued by Dimitri Gulia and Simon Janashia.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Both Georgian and Abkhaz law enshrines an official status of the Abkhaz language in Abkhazia.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The 1992 law of Georgia, reiterated in the 1995 constitution, grants Abkhaz the status of second official language in the territory of Abkhazia — along with Georgian.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] In November 2007, the de facto authorities of Abkhazia adopted a new law "on the state language of the Republic of Abkhazia" that mandates Abkhaz as the language of official communication.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The law is an attempt to amend a situation where up to a third of the ethnic Abkhaz population are no longer capable of speaking their ethnic language, and even more are unable to read or write it; instead, Russian is the language most commonly used in public life at present.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The literary language is based on the Abzhywa dialect.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] In some form or the other, all dialects are richer in phonemes than the standard Abzhywa dialect.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The only dialects spoken in Abkhazia are Abzhywa and Bzyp.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Northern dialects which are the basis for literary Abaza are spoken in Karachay-Cherkessia, while the other dialects such as Sadz are spoken in Turkey due to Russian invasions in the 19th century.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] While most differences are phonetic, differences in the lexicon are present, although mostly due to exterior contact.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Bzyp contains the most preserved lexicon, with few borrowings.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Abzhywa has adopted many loans from Kartvelian, specially Mingrelian; Sadz on the other hand has more words from Circassian.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Northern dialects in general have more loanwords from Persian, Arabic, Turkish and Circassian.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Abkhaz has a very large number of consonants (58 in the literary dialect), with three-way voiced/voiceless/ejective and palatalized/labialized/plain distinctions.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] By contrast, the language has only two phonemically distinct vowels, which have several allophones depending on the palatal and/or labial quality of adjacent consonants.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Labialised alveolo-palatal fricatives are found in the Bzyp and Sadz dialects of Abkhaz, but not in Abzhywa.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Plain alveolo-palatal consonants and the pharyngealised and labialised-pharyngealised uvular fricatives are unique to the Bzyp dialect.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The consonants highlighted in red and in brackets are the 4 kinds of labialisation described by Chirikba.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Found in the Bzyp and Sadz dialects of Abkhaz, but not in Abzhywa.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The nature of the vowels of Abkhaz is not clear.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Some linguists, characterise the vowel system as a 2 degree vertical vowel system; with the two vowels being distinguished by height, 'ә' being the high/close vowel, and 'а' being the low/open.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] This system would very closely resemble the one found in Adyghe.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The quality of 'ә' in this case, is usually represented as [ɨ] if the vowel is in a stressed position, and being unaffected by its neighbouring consonants.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Other linguists however, mainly Russian ones, describe the vowels differently.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] They describe the sound of 'ә' being completely different from [ɨ], and by their descriptions being closer to [ə].
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The 'а' is described as being particularly back, likely [ɑ].
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Abkhaz has used the Cyrillic script since 1862.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The first alphabet was a 37-character Cyrillic alphabet invented by Baron Peter von Uslar.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] In 1909 a 55-letter Cyrillic alphabet was used.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] A 75-letter Latin script devised by a Russian/Georgian linguist Nikolai Marr lasted for 2 years 1926–1928 (during the Latinization campaign).
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The Georgian script was adopted and used between 1938 and 1954, after that the initial Cyrillic alphabet, designed in 1892 by Dmitry Gulia together with Konstantin Machavariani and modified in 1909 by Aleksey Chochua, was restored to use.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The Latin alphabet in Abkhaz is currently not in Unicode.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Typical of Northwest Caucasian languages, Abkhaz is an agglutinative language that relies heavily on affixation.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] It has an ergative-absolutive typology, such that the subject of an intransitive verb functions identically to the object of a transitive verb.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Notably, Abkhaz expresses ergativity entirely through the ordering of subjects and objects within verb constructions rather than through overt case marking as most other ergative languages do.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] All Latin transliterations in this section utilize the system explicated in Chirikba (2003) (see Abkhaz alphabet for the details).
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Abkhaz, being an ergative language, makes a strong distinction between transitive and intransitive verbs, as well as dynamic and stative.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Stative verbs describe states of being, roughly analogous to copular phrases in English, as in дхәыҷуп (*d-x˚əčә́-wə-p* - "she is a child").
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Dynamic verbs express direct actions, functioning more closely to standard English verbs.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Dynamic verbs possess the full range of aspect, mood and tense forms, in contrast to statives, which do not.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Some verbs, called inversives, combine certain features of both stative and dynamic verbs.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Another important verbal distinction in Abkhaz is finite versus non-finite.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Finite verbs usually contain enough information to form a complete sentence, whereas non-finite verbs typically form dependent clauses.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Verb stems can be derived in a number of ways, including compounding, affixation, reduplication or conversion from another part of speech.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Roughly equivalent to the infinitive, or to a so-called "verbal noun," the **Masdar** form of the verb resembles the English gerund.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] It is formed by the addition of a specific suffix to a bare verb stem, -ра (*-ra*) for a dynamic verb and -заара (*-zaara*) for a stative.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] However, the fully conjugated personal Abkhaz verb forms are "templatic," with each grammatical distinction occupying a specific "slot" or "position" within the broader verb template.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Verbs are thus formed by the addition of various affixes to the verb stem; these affixes express such distinctions as transitivity, person and stative/dynamic quality, occupying rigid positions within the overall verb structure.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] There is a high degree of agreement between verbs and other parts of speech.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Not all of these elements will necessarily co-occur in every verb.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The individual parts of verb morphology are addressed below.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The first prefixing element of the verb complex expresses either the subject of an intransitive verb in the absolutive construction, or the direct object of a transitive verb in an ergative construction.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The following table illustrates the various agreement markers which can occupy the first position.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] These prefixes can either be in their long forms, containing the letters inside the parenthesis, or in the short forms that do not contain them.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] If the stress falls on the prefix, the long form is used.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] If the prefix is not followed by a consonant cluster, the short form is used.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] If the stress does not fall on the prefix, the short form is used.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] It is also possible for the possessive prefix ҽы́- (*čə́-*) in a reflexive construction or the relative prefix иы́- (*jә́-*) in a non-finite construction to occupy this position.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The second position is occupied by the indirect object or by the prefix аи- (*aj-*) for reciprocal pronouns equivalent to "each other" or "one another" in English.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] This position accommodates a number of prefixes.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Any indirect object occurring after the one in the second position occupies this position instead; a possessive prefix of stative verbs can also be placed here.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Where a possessive prefix exists in the first position, the reflexive prefix is placed here.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] This position is occupied by preverbal elements which are not an explicit part of the verb stem.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Preverbal elements that are explicitly attached to the verb stem take this position.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The agreement marker corresponding to the agent (the subject of a transitive verb) takes this position.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The negation prefix m- occupies this position in a dynamic verb construction.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The causative prefix r- takes the final position before the verb stem.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The first of the suffixing elements expresses adverbial information relating to "inside" (-la) or "outside" (-aa).
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Several aspect markers occupy this position as suffixes.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Several tense markers occupy this position, dependent upon whether the verb in question is stative or dynamic.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Dynamic verbs have a richly developed tense paradigm incorporating tense and aspect distinctions.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The table below illustrates these various dynamic tense forms using the verb агара (*agara* – "to take").
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Stative verbs, by contrast, lack this rich tense system, as illustrated below using the verb а́цәара (*ácºara* - "to be sleeping").
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The negation prefix m- occupies this position in a stative verb construction.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The final position in the verb complex can accommodate any one of several mixed purpose markers.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The **imperative** takes a few possible forms, depending upon the type of verb.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Dynamic verbs form the imperative by the addition of agreement suffixes to a bare verb stem; intransitives include the subject and indirect object makers, whereas transitives include the direct object and absolutive.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Stative verbs form the imperative simply by adding the durative suffix -z to the verb stem.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Abkhaz lacks diathetic opposition, and as such there is no true passive voice distinction.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Like verbs, Abkhaz nouns are formed by the addition of various prefixes and suffixes to a static noun stem.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Noun stems can be derived according to several different processes, including compounding, reduplication, or the addition of a derivational affix.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The affixes mark number, definiteness and possession, as well as some case-like elements.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] As with verbs, not all of these elements can occur at the same time.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The individual parts of noun morphology are addressed below.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] There is a range of definiteness in Abkhaz.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Those articles adhering to definite/generic categories appear as prefixes in the broader noun structure, whereas the indefinite is suffixed.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The absence of either article affix implies a zero reference implying universal quantifiers, or to express the total lack of a referent.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Definite and indefinite affixes may appear together in the same noun, implying that the referents are meant as a group or body.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] There are some semantic differences in article usage between the different dialects of Abkhaz.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] These are possessive prefixes which express grammatical person and noun class.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] They come in two forms, the full and short ones.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The full ones contain the vowels inside the parenthesis, whereas the short ones do not.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] These few prefixes add numeric information to the noun complex.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Often, this takes the form of a numeral.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Inflectional suffixes can follow each other sequentially.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Abkhaz distinguishes singular and plural; the singular is unmarked, whereas the plural is indicated by noun class-dependent suffixes.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] There are several pluralizing suffixes, but the two most commonly used refer generally to the human and non-human noun classes.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] There are instances where explicitly human nouns take non-human plural markers.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] There are also several plural endings that are of much narrower use.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The clitic -гьы (*-g’ə*) functions as an in-built coordinating conjunction.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Nouns in Abkhaz are classified broadly according to a human/non-human paradigm, with the human class itself further subdivided into masculine and feminine gender.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Gender is a fairly weak concept in Abkhaz grammar, and gender distinctions undergo a fair degree of neutralization in several contexts, including personal pronouns, verb agreement and possession marking.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] This class and gender system distinguishes Abkhaz from the other Northwest Caucasian languages.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Although there is no special vocative declension, the prefix уа- (*wa-*), when attached to a noun stem, can express a vocative form.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Similarly, the suffix -a can be added to a proper noun ending in a consonant to communicate respect and endearment.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Pronouns are not inflected, and verbal agreement is generally sufficient to indicate grammatical person.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] It is common in everyday speech to use a short version of the pronoun which omits the suffix -рá (*-rá*), although this is done less frequently with third-person pronouns.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] In addition to noun-marking, **possession** can be indicated by adding the suffix -тәы́ (*-t’˚ә́*) to the short version of a personal pronoun.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Morphologically, adjectives are very similar to nouns, differing only in their syntactic function.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Similarly to nouns, adjective stems can be derived by compounding, reduplication and affixation.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] When used attributively, adjectives follow the noun that they modify.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Predicative adjectives, or those derived by suffixation, precede the noun.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The possessive prefix r- is used to show possessive agreement.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] These suffixes are added to the adjective stem to show agreement with the noun being modified.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The comparative form of an adjective is formed using the comparative particle аиҳá (*ajhá* - "more"), which precedes the adjective.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] The superlative form is indicated by the intensifier suffix -ӡа.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] Дарбанзаалак ауаҩы дшоуп ихы дақәиҭны. Ауаа зегь зинлеи патулеи еиҟароуп. Урҭ ирымоуп ахшыҩи аламыси, дара дарагь аешьеи аешьеи реиԥш еизыҟазароуп.
[src:avar-language/abkhaz-language] "All human beings are born free and equal in dignity and rights.
[src:avar-language/ablative] In grammar, the **ablative case** (pronounced /ˈæblətɪv/ *AB-lə-tiv*; abbreviated **abl**) is a grammatical case for nouns, pronouns, and adjectives in the grammars of various languages.
[src:avar-language/ablative] It is used to indicate motion away from something.
[src:avar-language/ablative] In different languages it can additionally serve various other purposes, *e.g.*, to make comparisons (in Armenian).
[src:avar-language/ablative] The word "ablative" derives from the Latin *ablatus*, the (suppletive) perfect, passive participle of *auferre* "to carry away".
[src:avar-language/ablative] The ablative case is found in several language families, such as Indo-European (e.g.
[src:avar-language/ablative] Sanskrit, Latin, Albanian, Armenian, Punjabi), Turkic (e.g.
[src:avar-language/ablative] Turkish, Turkmen, Azerbaijani, Uzbek, Kazakh, Kyrgyz, Tatar), Tungusic (e.g.
[src:avar-language/ablative] Hungarian), and the Dravidian languages.
[src:avar-language/ablative] There is no ablative case in modern Germanic languages such as German and English.
[src:avar-language/ablative] There was an ablative case in the early stages of Ancient Greek, but it quickly fell into disuse by the classical period.
[src:avar-language/ablative] The ablative case in Latin (*cāsus ablātīvus*) appears in various grammatical constructions, including following various prepositions, in an ablative absolute clause, and adverbially.
[src:avar-language/ablative] The Latin ablative case was derived from three Proto-Indo-European cases: ablative (from), instrumental (with), and locative (in/at).
[src:avar-language/ablative] In Ancient Greek, there was an ablative case (ἀφαιρετικὴ πτῶσις *aphairetikē ptōsis*) which was used in the Homeric, pre-Mycenaean, and Mycenean periods.
[src:avar-language/ablative] It fell into disuse during the classical period and thereafter with some of its functions taken by the genitive and others by the dative.
[src:avar-language/ablative] The genitive case with the prepositions ἀπό *apó* 'away from' and ἐκ/ἐξ *ek/ex* 'out of' is an example.
[src:avar-language/ablative] German does not have an ablative case but, exceptionally, Latin ablative case-forms were used from the seventeenth to the nineteenth century after some prepositions, for example after *von* in *von dem Nomine*: ablative of the Latin loanword *nomen*.
[src:avar-language/ablative] Grammarians at that time, Justus Georg Schottel, Kaspar von Stieler, Johann Balthasar von Antesperg and Johann Christoph Gottsched, listed an ablative case (as the sixth case after nominative, genitive, dative, accusative and vocative) for German words.
[src:avar-language/ablative] They considered the dative case after some prepositions to be an ablative, as in *von dem Mann[e]* 'from the man, of the man' and *mit dem Mann[e]* 'with the man', while they considered the dative case after other prepositions or without a preposition, as in *dem Mann[e]*, to be a dative.
[src:avar-language/ablative] The ablative case is found in Albanian; it is the fifth case, *rasa rrjedhore*.
[src:avar-language/ablative] In Sanskrit, the ablative case is the fifth case (*pañcamī*) and has a similar function to that in Latin.
[src:avar-language/ablative] Sanskrit nouns in the ablative often refer to a subject "out of" which or "from" whom something (an action, an object) has arisen or occurred: *pátram **vṛkṣā́t** pátati* 'the leaf falls **from the tree**'.
[src:avar-language/ablative] It is also used for nouns in several other senses, as for actions occurring "because of" or "without" a certain noun, indicating distance or direction.
[src:avar-language/ablative] When it appears with a comparative adjective, (*śreṣṭhatamam* 'the best'), the ablative is used to refer to what the adjective is comparing: 'better than X'.
[src:avar-language/ablative] The modern Armenian ablative has different markers for each main dialect, both originating from Classical Armenian.
[src:avar-language/ablative] The Western Armenian affix -է *-ē* (definite -էն *-ēn*) derives from the classical singular; the Eastern Armenian affix -ից *-ic’* (both indefinite and definite) derives from the classical plural.
[src:avar-language/ablative] For both dialects, those affixes are singular, with the corresponding plurals being -(ն)երէ(ն) *-(n)erē(n)* and -(ն)երից *-(n)eric’*.
[src:avar-language/ablative] In Finnish, the ablative case is the sixth of the locative cases with the meaning "from, off, of": *pöytä – pöydältä* "table – off from the table".
[src:avar-language/ablative] It is an outer locative case, used like the adessive and allative cases, to denote both being on top of something and "being around the place" (as opposed to the inner locative case, the elative, which means "from out of" or "from the inside of").
[src:avar-language/ablative] With the locative, the receding object was near the other place or object, not inside it.
[src:avar-language/ablative] The Finnish ablative is also used in time expressions to indicate times of something happening (*kymmeneltä* "at ten") as well as with verbs expressing feelings or emotions.
[src:avar-language/ablative] The Finnish ablative has the ending *-lta* or *-ltä*, depending on vowel harmony.
[src:avar-language/ablative] The ablative case in Estonian is the ninth case and has a similar function to that in Hungarian.
[src:avar-language/ablative] The ablative case in Hungarian is used to describe movement away from, as well as a concept, object, act or event originating from an object, person, location or entity.
[src:avar-language/ablative] When used to describe movement away from a location, the case may only refer to movement from *the general vicinity* of the location and not from inside of it.
[src:avar-language/ablative] Thus, *a postától jövök* would mean one had been standing *next to* the post office before, not inside the building.
[src:avar-language/ablative] When the case is used to refer to the origin of a possible act or event, the act/event may be implied while not explicitly stated, such as *Meg foglak védeni a rabló**tól***: I will defend you from the robber.
[src:avar-language/ablative] The application of vowel harmony gives two different suffixes: *-tól* and *-től*.
[src:avar-language/ablative] These are applied to back-vowel and front-vowel words, respectively.
[src:avar-language/ablative] Hungarian has a narrower delative case, similar to ablative, but more specific: movement off/from a surface of something, with suffixes *-ról* and *-ről*.
[src:avar-language/ablative] In some situations simple ablative can have a "because of" meaning; in these situations, ablative can be optionally followed by the postposition *dolayı* 'because of'.
[src:avar-language/ablative] The ablative in Manchu is expressed through the suffix *-ci* and can also be used to express comparisons.
[src:avar-language/ablative] It is usually not directly attached to its parent word.
[src:avar-language/ablative] The ablative in Evenki is expressed with the suffix *-duk*.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] The **Abzakh dialect** (Adyghe: Абдзахабзэ; Kabardian: Абдзахэбзэ) is one of the Adyghe language dialects.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] The Abzakh dialect is spoken by the Abzakh which are one of the largest Circassian population in the diaspora outside Republic of Adygea alongside Shapsugs.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] Historically, Proto-Circassian possessed a distinct series of stops and affricates.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] Phase 1 (Spirantization): The original affricates weakened into fricatives or glottal stops.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] Phase 2 (Velar Palatalization): Historical palatalized velars shifted forward to fill the "gap" left by the changes in Phase 1.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] The following sections detail how these shifts occurred and provide comparative examples.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] The first major shift occurred in the Abzakh and Kabardian dialects, where the original affricate postalveolar consonants and affricate retroflex consonants underwent spirantization, becoming fricatives.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] One exception was that the original postalveolar ejective affricate [tʃʼ] ⟨чӏ⟩ did not just become a fricative; in Abzakh, it often debuccalized to a palatalized glottal stop ʔʲ ⟨ӏь⟩ (or simply ⟨ӏ⟩).
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] The following table details the timeline of this evolution specifically within Abzakh, showing how words shifted from Proto-Circassian, to an intermediate Proto-Abzakh stage, and finally to Modern Abzakh.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] Later on, after the original affricates had become fricatives or glottal stops, a gap was left in the postalveolar position.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] In the majority of Circassian dialects (including standard Adyghe and Kabardian), the historical velar consonants shifted forward to fill this gap.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] The velars ⟨гь⟩ [ɡʲ], ⟨кь⟩ [kʲ] and ⟨кӏь⟩ [kʲʼ] became the new palato-alveolar consonants ⟨дж⟩ [d͡ʒ], ⟨ч⟩ [t͡ʃ] and ⟨кӏ⟩ [t͡ʃʼ] respectively.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] The following table demonstrates how these words are distinct in archaic dialects (like Shapsug) but have merged or shifted in Standard Adyghe and Kabardian.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] The Voiceless velar fricative [x] becomes the aspirated Voiceless velar plosive [kʰ] (like English *c* in *car*, *cup*, *cop*, or *curse*) after the Voiceless postalveolar fricative [ʃ].
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] In this environment, the velar fricative undergoes hardening to become a plosive.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] This change only occurred in some Abzakh sub-dialects and in Bzhedug dialects.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] This should not be confused with the palatalized kʲ (like English *c* in *camera*, *cannon*, or *cow*).
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] In the Khakurinokhabl sub-dialect of Abzakh, the instrumental case has the suffix -мӏе (-mʔʲa) or -ӏе (-ʔʲa) unlike other dialects that has the suffix -мкӏэ (-mt͡ʃa) or -кӏэ (-t͡ʃa).
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] In the Standard Adyghe, The prefix зэкӏэ- means backward.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] In the Standard Adyghe, The prefix чӏэ- means under (toward under).
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] Саусырыкъо ахэмытэу нартхэр былымыхьэ кӏогъагъэх. Былымхэр къагъоти, къежьэжьыхи Къойданэм къэсыгъэх. Саусырыкъо дэмысыгъэу щытыти, къыхэкӏижьи, янэ дэжь къихьажьыгъ.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] — Сыгъашх, тян, — ыӏуагъ Саусырыкъо. — Сыгъашх, сыгъашх оӏо зэпыты, ущыс, модыкӏэ нартыхэр былым къахьи, Къойданым къэсыжьыгъэх, — къыриӏуагъ янэ.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] Нартымэ сырямыгъусагъэми, ащ къахьырэмэ анахьышӏуӏомкӏэ садэгощэн, тян, — ыӏуагъ.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] Пӏэстэ шыӏэ щтыгъ, лы жъогъэ щтыгъ, щыбжьый-шыгъу атетэкъуагъэу ӏанэм къытыригъэуцуагъэх янэ. Саусырыкъо пӏастэр ыфызи, псыр къыӏифыгъ, лыр ыутхыпкӏи мылыхэр къыпигъэтэкъуи ышхыгъ.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] — Ныбжьи нахь дэгъоу сыбгъэшхагъэп, тян, — ыӏуи къикӏижьыгъ.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] Саусырыкъо Тхъожъыем къытетӏысхьи, Къойданым кӏонэу ежьагъ. Саусырыкъо къакӏоу нартхэм залъэгъум, шӏэныгъэ иӏэу зы лӏы горэ ахэтыти: «Саусырыкъо мыгъо цӏыкӏур къэкӏозы, «фэсыжь апщи, нартхэ», зиӏокӏэ «тхьэуегъэпсэу» — шъуӏо нахь, «ахад» — шъумыӏо», — къариӏуагъ.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] Зэриӏуагъэм фэдэу, тыдэкӏэ ахэхьагъэми «тхьэуегъэпсэу» къыраӏуагъ нахь, «ахад» къыраӏуагъзп.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] Етӏанэ, Саусырыкъо губжъи, ежь зыфиӏорэр къыдэхъоу щытыти, щэщищ гъурӏи зишӏи шыӏэм зэтыригъэлӏагъэх.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] — Мэшӏо тӏэкӏу тэзгъэгъотырэр ӏэхьэгъу тшӏыщт зы ӏахьэкӏэ. — аӏуагъ нартымэ.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] — Сз шъозгъэгъотыщт, — ариӏуи, тау-таш горэм ӏугъо тӏэкӏу къыдихэу ылъэгъугъэти, Саусырыкъо ащ кӏуагъэ.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] Лэгъупышхом лы илъэу, пхъэцэӏитӏу, зы инырэ, зы цӏыкӏурэ пэлъэу, иныжъыри ащ къещэкӏигъэу пэӏулъэу къыӏухьагъ.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] Машӏом икъыпэхыкӏэу хъущтыр Саусырыкъо ымышӏэу егупшысэу щытызэ, Тхъожъыер къэгущыӏи: «Уишыӏядзэ къыӏехи, упкӏэ цуакъэ сфэшӏ. Бажьэм фэдэу зызгъэзэщт, цызэм фэдэу сыкъэкӏощт, лъэгонжэмышъхьэкӏэ зесыдзыхынызы, пхъэцакӏэ иным уемыӏэу, цӏыкӏур къашти, тхьыны тыкӏожьыщт, — къыриӏуагъ.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] Ишыӏядзэ къыӏихи, упкӏэ цуакъэ фишӏыгь. Къекӏуалӏи, Тхъожъыем лъэгонжэмышхьэкӏэ зыридзыхыгъ. Саусырыкъо пхъэцэкӏэ цӏыкӏум еӏэ шӏошӏызэ, иным еӏи, иныжъым тыригъафи, къыгъэущыгъ. Къэӏаби, Саусырыкъо рилъэшъохи шыр шъхьартӏупщэу хъугъэ, Саусырыкъуи иныжъым ипӏэшъхьагъ ӏилъхьагъ.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] — Сыд уилъэгъунэу укъызыфэкӏуагъэр? — ыӏуи иныжъыр къеупщӏыгъ.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] — Шыӏэ тылӏэти мэшӏо тӏзкӏу схьынэу сыкъэкӏуагъ, — ыӏуагъ Саусырыкъо.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] — Саусырыкъо ихьэгьо-шӏагъохэмэ ашышэу зы къаумэ къысаӏуи, устӏупщыжьыщт, — ыӏуагъ иныжъым.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] — Саусырыкъо ихьэгъо-шӏагъомэ ащышэу сэ зэхэсхыгъзу зы къаумэ къыосӏон, ау сэ ежь слъэгъугьахэп, — ыӏуагъ. — Саусырыкъо жьан щэрэхъыр къушъхьэм дарегъэхьые, къырарегъэфыхи, копкъышъхьэкӏэ еозы дефыежьы.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] Саусырыкъо дихьыен ылъэкӏыщтэпти, ежь иныжъым жьан щэрэхъыр къушъхьэм дихьий, Саусырыкъо къырыригьэшэхыгъ. Иныр копкъышъхьэӏе къеуи, къыдифыежьыгъ.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] — Ащ пэмыӏеу пшӏзрэ щыӏэмэ, къаӏо, — ыӏуагъ иным.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] — Цобзэ-шӏобзыр плъыжьыбзэу егъэплъызы, ыжэ кӏоцӏ делъхьазы егъэкӏуасэ аӏоу зэхэсхыгъэ, — риӏуагь.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] Иныжъым цобзэ-шӏобзыр плъыжьыбзэу ыгъэплъи, ыжэ дилъхьи, ыгъэкӏосагъ.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] — Сӏукӏоцӏ хъутэ-плъытэщти, ыгъэусэни, сигъэтхъэжьыгъ. Ай нэмыӏеу сы пшӏэрэ? — ыӏуи къеупщӏыгъ.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] — Ай нэмыӏеу, псыр егъажъо, псы жъуагъэм хэгьуалъхьэзы зегъэпскӏы.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] Иныжъым гъоплъэ хьэкъуашъокӏэ псыр къыгъажъуи, машӏор ӏешӏыхьагъэу хэгъуалъхьи зигъэпскӏыгъ.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] — Шъохъу-тӏэхъум сигъалӏэщтыгъ, сыдэу ӏэзэгъу шӏагъо къысэпӏуагъ, сиӏял, — къыриӏуагъ. — Джыри сыд ышӏэу зэхэпхыгъэр?
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] — Ай нэмыӏеу, ыхыкъын къэсэу псым зыхигьэщтыхьати, щэщ-мэфищэ хэтыщтыгъэ, етӏанэ къыкъутэти къыхэкӏижьыщтыгъ, — аӏоу зэхэсхыгъэ.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] — Адэ ар таущытэу ыгъэщтытыгъэ, сыд ышӏэщтыгъэр? — ыӏуи иныжъыр къеупщӏыгъ.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] — Сшӏэрэп, зыгорэ еӏошъы псыр егъэщты аӏоу зэхэсхыгъэ, — ыӏуагъ Саусырыкъо.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] — Псым хэуцу, — ыӏуи ытыкъыны къэсэу псым хигъэуцуагъ.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] Ежь Саусырыкъо ышӏэу щытыти, щэщищым къэхъущт щтырыгъуӏир къышӏи, иныжъыр хигъэщтыхьагъ.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] — Къеӏ, — ыӏуи къызеӏэм, мылыр къыгъэцӏацӏэу, къыгъачэу хъугъэ.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] — Зэ зыгъэбыяу, щыгъупшагъэ сшӏыгъэ, — ыӏуагъ Саусырыкъо. — Саусырыкъо мылыр къыхичыти, псы къытыригъэлъадэщтыгъ, хьауарзэ хитакъоти, ыгъзщтыжьыти, къытыригъэсэжьыщтыгъэ.
[src:avar-language/abzakh-dialect] Ащ фэдэу ышӏи: — Къеӏ, нныжъ, —зыреӏом, къьыкӏаӏи шъхьзкӏэ мылыр къыфэгъэхъыягъэп.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Adamawa Fulfulde was originally brought to Cameroon in the early parts of the 19th century during a religious war (Jihad) that was launched by Usman dan Fodio from Northern Nigeria.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] It is an Atlantic language that belongs to the Niger–Congo language family.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] The speakers of the language are the Fulani people.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] The language itself is divided into a number of sub-dialects: Maroua, Garoua, Ngaondéré, Kambariire, Mbororoore, and Bilkire.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] In Sudan, the language is spoken mainly in Blue Nile, Gedaref, and Sennar states with some communities of speakers also found in North Kordofan and South Kordofan states.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] In South Sudan, it is spoken in Western Bahr el Ghazal state by Ambororo cattle herders.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] In Chad, it is spoken in Lac Léré Department in the Mayo-Kebbi Ouest Region.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] In Nigeria, it is spoken in Adamawa and Taraba states.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] While in Cameroon the language is widespread across the Far North and Northern regions of the country.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] The word order for Adamawa Fulfulde is SOV (subject–object–verb).
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Adamawa Fulfulde is mostly written in a modified Arabic script, in the tradition of Ajami script, that it shares with many other languages such as Hausa language, and many other languages in Sub-Sahara Africa.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Writing Fulfulde with Arabic script has a long tradition and old manuscripts are found in all of West Africa.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Latin alphabet is also used for writing of Adamawa.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] The usage of Latin is a lot more recent, only coming to existence with the arrival of European Christian.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Still, in Cameroon, Arabic alphabet remains more popular for writing of Adamawa Fulfulde than Latin.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] The Adamawa Fulfulde Ajami alphabet is the result of many decades of efforts to standardize, starting from the 1960s.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] By the 1990s, the orthography was well established.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] In 1998, at the JCMWA/MICCAO conference in Ngaoundéré, Cameroon, over 100 representatives from 14 West African countries agreed that this orthography would be a good standard for writing the Fulfulde language with Arabic script.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] The alphabet consists of 33 basic letters, 28 plus *hamaza* from Arabic, and 4 are new letters created for use in Fulfulde.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] 10 of the Arabic letters are only used for writing Arabic loanwords, and have no use for writing indigenous Fulfulde words.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] This letter does come in the beginning of words as a vowel diacritic carrier for common Arabic loanwords.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Character unique to Fulfulde, not found in Arabic.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Pronounced as [θ] in Arabic, but as [s] in Fulfulde.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] This letter is pronounced as [h] in Fulfulde, and is used for representing the sound [h] (except in Arabic loanwords).
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] The latter is only used in Arabic loanwords in Fulfulde.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Pronounced as [x] in Arabic, but as [h] or [x] in Fulfulde.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] This letter has a variation of pronunciations in different local dialects.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Pronounced as [sˤ] in Arabic, but as [s] in Fulfulde.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Pronounced as [dˤ] in Arabic, but as [d] in Fulfulde.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] This is the local indigenous innovation in the Adamawa dialectical area.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Pronounced as [q] in Arabic, but as [k~g] in Fulfulde.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] , in which case it will not carry any diacritic.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] This letter serves two functions, either as a consonant [w], or it lengthens vowels [o] or [u].
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] This letter serves two functions, either as a consonant [j], or it lengthens vowel [i].
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Letter used for lengthening of vowel [e].
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] In Adamawa Fulfulde, there are 4 prenasalized consonants.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Prenasalized consonants are written as a digraph (combination of two consonants).
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] The first letter of the digraph representing a prenasalized consonant cannot take any diacritic, including zero-vowel diacritic *sukun* '◌ْ‎'.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Like other languages that have historically been written within what's known as the Ajami tradition, there is a full relaince on diacritics for writing vowels.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] In Arabic there are only three diacritics, which represent [a] '◌َ‎', [u] [i] '◌ُ‎', and [i] '◌ِ‎'.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] The general tradition is that when there are vowels that don't exist in Arabic, new diacritics are created.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] In Adamawa Fulfulde these include the Quranic imāla '◌ٜ‎' for vowel [e], and a special diacritic '◌ٛ‎' for vowel [o].
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Unlike Arabic orthography, or other Arabic-derived scripts, in Ajami tradition, all diacritics are written.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Even letters that don't have any vowels, are written with a *zero-vowel/sukun* '◌ْ‎' diacritic.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] Vowels are lengthened by combining the diacritic with a follow-up letter, just as is the tradition in Arabic.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] These follow-up letters are written without a diacritic.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] ' can be part of a digraph representing prenasalized consonants.
[src:avar-language/adamawa-fulfulde] In these instances, these two letters are written without a diacritic.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] It is spoken mainly in the western and southern parts of the Russian Caucasus republic of Dagestan, and the Balaken, Zaqatala regions of north-western Azerbaijan.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] Some Avars live in other regions of Russia.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] There are also small communities of speakers living in the Russian republics of Chechnya and Kalmykia; in Georgia, Kazakhstan, Ukraine, Jordan, and the Marmara Sea and Maraş region of Turkey.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] It is spoken by about 1,200,000 people worldwide.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] UNESCO classifies Avar as vulnerable to extinction.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] It is one of six literary languages of Dagestan, where it is spoken not only by the Avar, but also serves as the language of communication between different ethnic and linguistic groups.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] Glottolog lists 14 dialects of Avar, some of which correspond to the villages where they are spoken.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] There are competing analyses of the distinction transcribed in the table with the length sign ⟨ː⟩.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] Length is part of the distinction, but so is articulatory strength, so they have been analyzed as fortis and lenis.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] The fortis affricates are long in the fricative part of the contour, e.g. [tsː] (tss), not in the stop part as in geminate affricates in languages such as Japanese and Italian [tːs] (tts).
[src:avar-language/avar-language] Laver (1994) analyzes e.g. [t͡ɬː] as a two-segment affricate–fricative sequence [t͡ɬɬ] (/t𐞛ɬ/ = /tɬɬ/).
[src:avar-language/avar-language] Avar has five phonemic vowels: /a e i o u/.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] In Avar, accent is contrastive, free and mobile, independent of the number of syllables in the word.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] There were some attempts to write the Avar language in the Georgian alphabet as early as the 14th century.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] The use of the Perso-Arabic script for representing Avar in marginal glosses began in the 15th century.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] The use of Arabic, which is known as *ajam*, is still known today.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] Peter von Uslar developed a Cyrillic-based alphabet, published in 1889, that also used some Georgian-based letters.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] Many of its letters have not been encoded in Unicode.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] As part of Soviet language re-education policies in 1928 the Ajam was replaced by a Latin alphabet, which in 1938 was in turn replaced by the current Cyrillic script.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] Essentially, it is the Russian alphabet plus one additional letter called *palochka* (*stick*, Ӏ), originally the digit 1 on a manual typewriter.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] The palochka is not included in common computer keyboard layouts, and is often replaced with a capital Latin letter i ( *I* ) or occasionally a small Latin letter L ( *l* ) rather than the digit *1*.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] The Avar language is usually written in the Cyrillic script.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] The Avar Latin alphabet was originally monocameral.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] Note that there is no distinction between a cedilla as in ⟨ţ⟩ and a straight tick as in ⟨ⱪ⟩; the graphic forms of the letters vary by publication, and *k* may have a cedilla or *t* a tick.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] One feature of Avar Arabic alphabet is that similar to alphabets such as Uyghur and Kurdish, the script does not omit vowels and does not rely on diacritics to represent vowels when need be.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] Instead, modified letters with dot placement and accents have been standardized to represent vowels.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] Thus, Avar Arabic script is no longer an "impure abjad" unlike its parent systems (Arabic, Persian, and Ottoman), it now resembles a proper "alphabet".
[src:avar-language/avar-language] While this was not the case for most of the several centuries during which Arabic alphabet has been used for Avar, this has become the case in the latest and most common conventions.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] This was indeed not the case at the time of writing of a linguistic article for the Journal of the Royal Asiatic Society in 1881.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] As an example, in Avar Arabic Script, four varieties of the letter *yāʼ* (ی) have been developed, each with a distinct function.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] Nevertheless, Avar Arabic script does retain two diacritics.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] First is "shadda" (ـّـ), used for gemination.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] While in Cyrillic, two back to back letters, including digraphs are written, in Arabic script, shadda is used.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] Second diacritic in use in Avar Arabic script is ḍammah (ـُـ).
[src:avar-language/avar-language] In Arabic, Persian, and historically in Ottoman Turkish, this diacritic is used to represent [o] or [u].
[src:avar-language/avar-language] But in Avar, this diacritic is used for labialization [◌ʷ] and not for any sort of vowel.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] So, it is the case that this diacritic is used in conjunction with a follow-up vowel.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] For example, the sound "зва" [zʷa] is written as "زُا".
[src:avar-language/avar-language] This diacritic can optionally be used in conjunction with shadda.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] For example, the sound "ссвa" [sʷːa] is written as "سُّا".
[src:avar-language/avar-language] If a word starts with a vowel, if it's an [a] sound, it is written with *alif* "ا".
[src:avar-language/avar-language] Otherwise, the vowel needs to be preceded by a "vowel carrier", which is *hamza-ya'* (ئـ).
[src:avar-language/avar-language] No need for such a carrier in the middle of words.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] Below table demonstrates vowels in Avar Arabic Script.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] Avar is an agglutinative language, of SOV order.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] Adverbs do not inflect, outside of inflection for noun class in some adverbs of place: e.g. the /b/ in /ʒani-b/ 'inside' and /t͡se-b-e/ 'in front'.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] Adverbs of place also distinguish locative, allative, and ablative forms suffixally, such as /ʒani-b/ 'inside', /ʒani-b-e/ 'to the inside', and /ʒani-sa/ 'from the inside'. /-go/ is an emphatic suffix taken by underived adjectives.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] The literary language is based on the болмацӏ (*bolmaⱬ*)—*bo* 'army, country' and *maⱬ* 'language'—the common language used between speakers of different dialects and languages.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] The *bolmaⱬ* in turn was mainly derived from the dialect of Khunzakh, the capital and cultural centre of the Avar region, with some influence from the southern dialects.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] Nowadays the literary language is influencing the dialects, levelling out their differences.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] The most famous figure of modern Avar literature is Rasul Gamzatov, the People's Poet of Dagestan.
[src:avar-language/avar-language] Translations of his works into Russian have gained him a wide audience all over the former Soviet Union.
